The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a minikindergarten here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the employees of Arch.Design since last year.
The design and architectural office Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known Brno buildings originate, counted from the first drafts for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its company mini-kindergarten.
In wise foresight, because most of his 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is interested in the fact that the projecters and architects return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the opportunity to work shorter, the kindergarten is another bonus Arch.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for civil engineers and architects to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company's mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (contributions of CZK 2.8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and for a period of 2 years qualified staff and operation are provided.
After using up the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the Minikindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with Economy Rating providing active assistance in the implementation of applications.
The children are looked after by fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can attend children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but the day alternates over several children.
The kindergarten business is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although individual education and care are involved, the programme content in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme for pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, and they also learn English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
The parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus the stress is eliminated when the children are late picked up from a far away kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also emerging here.
Arch.Design thus ranks among the Czech companies, which offer clear benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personal marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants the house with its organic forms got the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colours, the unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft lines, all of these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colours and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only with a closer look that one notices that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-out order.
At night, the entire façade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and intricate shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and bars.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district, on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was built by the renovation of a house dating back to 1877, executed by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper conversion.
The Casa Batlló apartment building, however, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on its drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of reality arose and the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other painters and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the Park Güell, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given the nickname "Knochenhaus" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "guy house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of Saint George, the Patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces for the house, which was unique at that time.
It's a bit bizarre. Her 45-degree tilt is already on.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all of the building regulations of the time and was by no means misled by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified at the completion that they demanded a remedy.
Among other things, the councillors stumbled upon the fact that the building with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the city's request for this to happen - and Josep Batlló applied for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the reconstruction, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by the opening of the salon doors and thus a larger society could chat comfortably without having to forego a certain intimacy during more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, the house received a rather unusual roof and two additional floors.
Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is covered and the courtyards are impressive.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners decided only in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was discovered that this was a quite profitable business, the visits were kept, even extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a pappenstiel, it amounts to 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the house dwellers and visit him at home.
