More and more parents want human surveillance devices to keep the kids under control
The fear for one's own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented to search for cars, can locate people just as well, which would also be helpful in such cases, as in the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box, but soon it will not be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have been frightened by the disappearance of Anička, so they look for ways and means to better protect their children.
Also for the price of an impairment of their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not about spying around, but about an effective means of reducing the probability that tragedy will occur," says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that in individual cases such devices can be misused, for example if you put it in someone's pocket without him knowing about it, but we have not had such a case so far."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," adds Pilin.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, he simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they don't want to be controlled."
"At the beginning, the mobile phones already aroused great expectations among parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices," says Ms. Bočková.
In their opinion, it is also controversial whether such an institution actually helps in the event of an attack.
