A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger appear to be at less risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published by the British Journal of Cancer on Wednesday.
This is supposed to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty," said Ros Eeles, co-author of the study, professor at the Cancer Research Institute at Warwick University.
The finger could help to determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if genetic risks or other risk factors are present, such as family health stress, Ms Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but at the same time also 3000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer was valid as for 19 percent of men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, for men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, for men up to sixty even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which already form at prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone in particular accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said that he was familiar with this study, yet he did not consider the relationship between the finger length and the risk of cancer to be "completely proven".
