Maestro-Gelatiere Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal properties of the perfect ice cream.
The decisive factor is not only good taste, but also the silky suppleness and good consistency.
During his training, Luciano does not forget the icing on the cake of the national and even southern superstructure: "Italian gelato is simply the best - and then there is a lot of romance."
The first step to manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano dips the basic ingredients milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixer, which heats everything to 85 degrees with an electronic program and then immediately cools down to four degrees.
Then he turns a cock on the machine, and out comes a pasteurized white base cream, basis for all types of milk ice cream.
Immediately the lecturer is attacked with questions: Can ice cream only be produced with natural substances without a stabilizer?
How can one give free rein to one's own desire for experimentation?
Luciano warns against being misled by the spirit of the times.
Those who talk about ice cream "only from natural ingredients" may still have used stabilizers - usually a natural product, such as guar gum from the guar bean.
Of course, you can also produce ice without a stabilizer, but then it has to be sold within a day, otherwise it accumulates in itself, and the customer bites on all the ice grains.
Certain variations on the base mass are allowed.
It becomes more exciting with the aromas.
For the taste in the ice cream Maestro Luciano distinguishes between the ingredients that are bought in the fruit department or at the sweets of the supermarket.
There are also powders and pastes.
"The suppliers will all try to give you dozens of flavored additives."
"But you should just experiment."
Either with the fruit sorbets with sugar and fresh fruits.
Or just with the ice cream from the white base mass, which turns with eggs into a yellow cream and with cocoa powder as the basis for all possible chocolate temptations.
Now the students are allowed to go to the ice machines.
Luciano makes four different kinds of vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut ice cream - with or without eggs in the base, with more or less vanilla flavour or other natural additives.
The same experiment is also being carried out on the varieties of fruit ice cream.
More flavoring substances, more fruit puree - taste is not necessarily better.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily taste more nutty if it contains more hazelnuts.
The most popular kiwi ice cream is the working group that uses more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizer.
Only a balanced mixture really highlights the taste of a gelato, says Luciano.
Ice cream production is a computational task: If peach puree is used with a lot of sugar, the sugar content in the basic recipe must be reduced.
An extra portion of sugar is required for lemon ice cream.
Luciano draws out a device with which he determines the sugar content of the fruit varieties (winers measure the Oechsle in grape must).
Fortunately, tables make computing easier.
Making ice does not require as much physical effort as before.
Not only the device helps for automatic production of the base mass.
There is also a device in which the finished ice mixture is creamy at the same time and cooled to minus temperatures.
Despite all automation, small breakdowns do not fail.
The Brazilian Gustavo grudges himself and his course colleagues from top to bottom with fruit puree when the oversized rod mixer gets out of his control.
"In every class," says Maestro Luciano, "it's just a matter of time before something like this happens."
