"What happens here is ecological warfare," says Celestine Akpobari sinisterly: "We live in constant danger to health."
The war comparison is appropriate.
The settlement area of the Ogoni is a battleground that has been fought for decades: here more than 60 years ago the first explorers from Europe invaded, here in the 1980s the first resistance was organized with the later executed writer Ken Saro-Wiwa, here the Shell company had to stop its production in 1993 because it became too dangerous for its oil workers.
Even today, the Company is denied a return to Ogoniland: while more than two million barrels of black gold are pumped daily from the entire delta region of the triple size of Switzerland, with over 5000 drilling wells and 7000 kilometres of pipelines, the oil fields in Ogoniland are broken, and the Group is in too unstable a position.
Every few hundred metres steel frames rise like bizarre sculptures out of the water: "Christ-trees" are called the heads of the holes far too tender.
They are up to 50 years old, most corroded to the mark.
Again and again such a drilling head breaks apart, says Akpobari, then a constant stream of crude oil flows into the water.
According to expert estimates, more than two billion liters have flowed into the Delta's ecosystem in 50 years: year after year, the amount of oil that entered the sea off Alaska in the accident of the supertanker "Exxon Valdez" 21 years ago - one of the greatest environmental disasters in human history.
Those who are to be held responsible for the ongoing eco-GAU are disputed about this.
While the Shell Group is responsible for more than 90 percent of the pollution caused by sabotage and organized oil theft, environmentalists see drilling heads and leaking pipelines as the main cause.
Shell set significantly lower safety standards in Nigeria than usual in the world, the US scientist Richard Steiner accused the company in 2008: The rate of defects on the lines alone is "many times higher than elsewhere".
In a place that looks like an abandoned, oil-lubricated workshop under the open sky from a distance, figures emerge from the mangroves: they are stark naked and oil-lubricated to the neck.
Under one of the many barrels, which are partly connected with tubes, partly arbitrarily scattered on the premises, a fire flickers: an illegal small refinery.
In the barrel, the crude oil is heated over the fire for several hours, explains Michael, head of the group.
At first, gasoline penetrates through the pipes into the trap, later dripping kerosene and finally diesel at the end of the line.
Michael and four employees produce up to four barrels of 300 litres of diesel every day: "That brings us 34,000 Naira" - around 22 dollars.
The Delta people use the chronic fuel shortage in the largest oil state in Black Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
The illegal cookers can still undercut the ridiculously low price of diesel with just under 40 euro cents per litre: because they get their raw material for free.
It comes from "Bunkers" that tap the pipeline across Ogoniland: this is how experts say the country loses at least 16 million litres of crude oil every day in the entire Niger Delta.
However, only a small part of the temporarily stored raw material is illegally refined: the lion's share is filled by organised criminal networks, including politicians and high-ranking military, in tankers and sold on the world market.
The activist Akpobari believes that the debate as to whether the environmental catastrophe is more due to the relocation of the population or the lax mode of production is purely academic.
"If the oil companies had not been perceived as invaders and had not destroyed the livelihoods of the fishermen so thoroughly, there would be no sabotage, no theft and illegal refineries."
In the meantime, however, the Ogoni's relationship with Shell was destroyed to such an extent that only a withdrawal of the company could be considered: "Perhaps other nationalities like the Chinese might turn out to be better."
Michael's getting nervous.
"Maximum time for you to disappear," says the muscular oilman.
"The soldiers can come any minute."
If the illegal oil refiners are caught by the armed forces' special unit, they are not threatened with arrest, but a painful bribe.
Like all Nigerians, the soldiers who come mainly from the country's north also want to benefit from the raw material.
"This damn stuff has brought our country to the dog in every way," says Akpobari.
