Around midnight on September 5 to 6, 2007, at least four Israeli F-15 I fighter planes attack a mysterious, cube-shaped building in Syria.
It stands on the banks of the Euphrates River; the nearest larger city, 30 kilometers away, is Dair as-Saur.
Their name appears in documents from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) regarding the reactor that Syria allegedly built in the square with the help of North Korea, hidden in a valley that is draining from the electricity.
According to a briefing from the CIA at the end of April 2008, the reactor, also known as the nearby town of el-Kibar, would have been well suited to producing plutonium - from which nuclear weapons could be built.
For other purposes, however, the technique from the 1950s is hardly suitable.
The CIA performed a video presentation with fuzzy satellite images.
