It also denied the inspectors a second inspection into el-Kibar and access to the rubble of the bombed building.
But Israel also remains silent.
"We will never comment on this," recently confirmed Prime Minister Ehud Olmert, who was in office at the time of the attack.
As a result, the investigation of the case has been dragging on since June 2008 and "is increasingly developing into a serious credibility problem for the authority", as a high-ranking Western diplomat admits at the headquarters of the IAEA in Vienna - after all, there is a serious violation of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, over which the IAEA is monitoring.
