In the weeks after your husband’s sudden death, Argentina’s president, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that pushed her popularity rate up by 20 points to over 50%, the highest value since her election in 2007.
Whether this will help her to re-election next year, however, depends on whether the visibly grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who guided economic policy even after his wife’s election, often drew up budget plans that did not fully take into account tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra income at their own discretion.
On paper, the Fernández government lost the majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition is divided and Kirchner's death after a heart attack on 27 October led to further discord.
Some regime critics from the ranks of the ruling Peronists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
But after chaotic meetings (where one parliamentarian slapped another's face and others accused the government of bribery), Congress failed to adopt the 2011 budget.
"I won't discuss it," the president said.
The 2010 budget now also applies to next year, which gives the President even more opportunity to spend money at his own discretion.
The economy is running hot: it will probably grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but many private estimates - and wage demands of the trade unions - drive the value to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003, when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty reduction its main objectives, not the reduction of inflation.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, harassed the private sector, and cleaned the National Institute of Statistics and Census INDEC, which then embellished the official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández now take a more moderate path?
It has called on the private sector and trade union leaders to talk.
And according to official statements, wage increases are to be limited to 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina's agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
But inflation undermined the growth boost by a major devaluation in 2002.
For this reason, Cristina Fernández may want to reconnect Argentina financially with the rest of the world.
At the beginning of this year, the government reached an agreement with securities holders who had rejected the country's previous debt restructuring in 2001.
Now Fernández seems to be pushing for an agreement with the donors from the Paris Club, to which she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always rejected a review by the IMF, as is customary elsewhere.
But last month, the Minister of Economic Affairs, Amado Boudou, announced that the Fund will provide "technical support" for the creation of a new national consumer price index, which looks like this is the first step towards cleaning up the INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active after her term of office has ended even without the support of her husband.
If so, it needs the support of the middle class, which largely has enough of Kirchnerism.
When the Argentines return from their summer vacations in March, the wave of sympathies brought to her will have faded.
If she wants to win another election, she has to decide whether or not to quietly pick up many of her husband's political decisions.
