Arsenic-resistant microbes could enable new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is a sign in their view that life is possible even without the elements previously considered necessary for life.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"He needs phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"This makes it very special, even though it is almost a kind of 'foreign' way of life," explained Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which will be published in the online edition of Science on Thursday.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in California's Mono Lake continues to grow even if it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"One wonders what else is possible," said the co-author of the report Ariel D. Anbar from Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists must recognize life and its forms, says Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details on the discovery were disclosed gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems organisms can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements, and that the 'standard elements', which we believe are absolutely vital, are not necessarily fixed," explained Charles Cockell, Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that one element can be replaced by another in basic biochemical processes and structures," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA's Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake due to its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, it assumed that microbes exposed to both may replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of the arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic has a different effect than phosphorus. It enters our biochemical system, where it smears almost everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing arsenic concentration. It adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, it can also survive in arsenic, showing that an arsenic-based form of life can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, where arsenic occurs more frequently.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a lecturer in microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but there has been no working example yet.
Arsenic occurred more frequently in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have developed differently from the early Earth age," says Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
