Prosecutors of the Department of Justice acquit Senator John Ensign of the charges against him after his affair with a former electoral assistant and his attempt to get her husband to lobby, the senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday.
This decision ends the most serious legal charge against Senator Ensign, the Republican from Nevada. Until the scandal, which caused headlines nationwide and dampened his career, he was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012.
Senator Ensign's office announced that he was "very pleased" with the verdict after the one-year investigation.
However, the Senate's ethics committee could still impose a disciplinary penalty.
According to Ensign's lawyers, they were informed by the Department of Justice that the investigations against Senator Ensign had been terminated and that there were no further charges in this matter.
The Department of Justice did not want to comment on the case.
The verdict was a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Ministry of Justice. In their opinion, there was sufficient evidence that Ensign had disregarded the lobbying ban.
Interviews, e-mails, and other material disclosed for the first time in the New York Times in October 2009 gave rise to the suspicion that Ensign Douglas Hampton, one of his electoral assistants, helped to make lucrative assignments to buy his silence over an affair with Hampton's wife Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton was a treasurer during the Ensign election campaign.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton to work. According to the documents and interrogations, he took over Hampton's lobbying after hiring them.
As Hampton was recently on Ensign's election team, he was not allowed to lobby for a year for his former employer or the entire Senate.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called ban on revolving door lobbyism.
According to the published evidence, "it seems to be a collusion and a violation of the revolving door statutes," says Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer specializing in defending clients targeted by the government.
While the Department of Justice officially refused to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the ministry seemed very cautious in taking political charges after a variety of defeats that were followed with great interest by the media, including last year's decision to drop the charges against former Senator Ted Stevens for misconduct by the prosecutor.
Prosecutors "are obviously frightful," said Melanie Sloan, chairman of the Association "Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington" (an organization whose aim is to combat corruption in US parliamentary and government circles), a group of lawyers who brought various charges against Mr. Ensign to justice.
"This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Chief Defender of Mr. Ensign, said in an interview that he had received a telephone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another one the next day that he was told that the ministry would not bring any lawsuits against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defenders had cooperated with the prosecutors to convince them that, as his office repeated in a statement on Wednesday, the senator had "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to explain in more detail the legal arguments he had made to the prosecutors.
"I don't think I'm going to go into the conversation details between the Department of Justice and me. Just so much to say: we think we've made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Electoral Commission decided to close the investigation into a separate lawsuit filed by the Ethics Group that resulted in a payment of $96,000 from Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons in violation of the Federal Electoral Act.
The election commission said there was not enough evidence that the money was something other than a gift.
NV Energy, a large Nevada company that for a long time supported the senator, was one of the companies where Mr. Hampton found lobbyist work thanks to the help of Mr. Ensign.
An e-mail from December 2008 proves that after Mr. Hampton's company moved on as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensing's chief of staff, John Lopez, had an interview with Mr. Hampton, in which he informed him that he was "anklopfe" to the Interior Department about a matter.
Mr. Ensign also met with Mr. Hampton and another customer from Nevada, Allegiant Air, for lunch and asked the Transport Minister to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after the latter had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby.
Last year, when information about this affair came to the public for the first time, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and gave up his position in the Senate, where he had ranked fourth among Republicans.
After he hadn't noticed for many months, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he was seeking a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign is no longer the target of police investigation, his press secretary, Jennifer Cooper, the senator hoped that the Ethics Commission would very quickly follow the example of the Ministry of Justice and stop its investigation.
"Senator Ensign is looking forward to continuing his hard work in the service of the people of Nevada," she said.
