Can politeness connect the separating?
After a campaign of swearing and negativity, little courtesy broke out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of genuine two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before one quickly returns to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not bring a breakthrough on the major issues that had to be addressed during the so-called "lame duck session", the meeting at the end of a period of government in which no decisions were taken.
After all that is heard, it was not a polite discussion between two sides nor a consideration of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partisan score.
The public meeting of the President's Deficit Commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that persist between the members.
It seems clear that a close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that masks the ideological divide that continues to separate members from each other.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - one of which calls for the other sign of willingness to cooperate and compromise, while one tries to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a renewed party war.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to be expected to change the atmosphere that prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, the November election voted Washington mildly for at least a short time.
"No question, the tone has changed," said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration, who is now working for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"This is inevitable after elections.
Elections arouse party passions that die again.
And that's a good thing."
On some issues, especially those on the "lame duck session" agenda, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution."
Bush's tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one supports that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or even all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, even if only because the Republicans cannot afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After the meeting in the White House on Tuesday, the optimism has increased that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratify the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of Brookings Insituation warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of lame duck session" does not necessarily lead to a lasting cooperation of the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of non-conformity is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation," he said.
Wehner is also sceptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that politeness leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what is happening from now until 2012, as a prelude, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and the tea party voters whose formation served.
However concerned the Republican leaders may be that they are playing too high a poker, they know that they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and override health reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include a tax reform and raising some taxes, as well as raising the retirement age and lowering government spending.
Vice-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that they can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan the official recommendation and they are fighting very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the panel, because in financial matters, at least today, there is little scope or sympathy for compromises.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first battle will take place next year in the form of party clashes when Republicans challenge Obama with regard to the state budget, taxes, and health system, later followed by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
Public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must be careful about the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanism and polarization are greater today than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and Congress Republicans than President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a pure prelude to a far wider election in 2012.
From this point of view, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the issues that still separate the two.
