Zapatero and the Red Line of Germany
Berlin has chosen to retain the euro, but at the same time has set conditions for the whole of the European Union.
Market tensions have triggered a dual response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adaptation measures, starting with tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, the regulation of temporary work companies or the abolition of the 426 euro support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatisation of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former President Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, this is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany takes on a fundamentally new perspective for shaping our future, which clashes with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German mark - although that sounds more like science fiction at the moment - , supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third is a restructuring of the euro according to German proposals, which means more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; penalisation of countries that exceed the requirements; possibly the cessation of payments by some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled a constitutional reform off its sleeve to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of the drifting apart between what Germany considered necessary (strict fiscal plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was set by the Central European country when Merkel painfully pushed out the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the published opinion were absolutely against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, Merkel has come out again with a clear position in the last few days of October, calling for reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country to be saved while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, driving the Irish crisis and all the following.
However, their proposal, albeit a little sweeter, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will allow these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It says to everyone that, even if unpopular measures need to be taken now, the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area, in which the countries that are opposed to it will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and, in this case, the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to take a hard growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness as well as positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as led by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we'd do a bad thing not to understand.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat on ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will be more calm.
And that we will make use of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in his own house has paved its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like anything would change.
Among the possibilities that have been considered is that we should leave the euro area, which is full of little serious countries, not to be excluded.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and regulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show ingenuity, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The supposed exclusion of two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the game of November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsportsmanlike act or not and whether both players might be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls for the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will comply with the prescribed penalty in the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the coach of the club, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules, but in this sport it is followed.
Part of the debate about the case presented is due to the fact that a team from the Real Madrid football club (who, in his anthem, pretended to be noble and honorable and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long story than theatrical and provocative technicians.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this practice, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a rule bypass. Indeed, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sporting spirit should be investigated.
The sport spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the opposing players get an unjustified benefit from the counter-team. Nor did this happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by false play or rule avoidance, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and happily accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders derived from the deliberate fouls.
It should be pointed out here that the rival was not placed in a less favourable position, nor was there any advantages for the game being played, as the obvious result of this action was that his own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, to a certain degree uncertain advantage, since the team could eventually also withdraw. Furthermore, players with this approach receive a sanction and move into the second card cycle, in which they withdraw less than in the first cycle due to the accumulation of cards with one card.
So it is not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to maximise the benefits of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent any sanction (this would actually be a clear case of rule avoidance), they wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or escaping punishment.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the rule environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemics came about as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
