China maintains its greenhouse gas reduction targets
At COP16, China’s representative said that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and maintained its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China is offering to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, assures Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured his country that he had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He stated that over the last four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he said that China would not change its goals, but would work on this issue together with the international community.
He said that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
He said that progress had been made in all aspects, including the adoption last year of a new Energy Act, which included the objectives of reducing the emission of gases.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, state authorities had cooperated with those of the central government and municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, effective use of energy and reduction of emissions.
He also carried out, started or completed several years of plans, both those funded by the Chinese government and those that received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the programme for the effective use of energy, which has been introduced over the past five years and which has received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and from private hands.
There is also a provincial project on climate change, another on the exchange of traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs and another on mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, a scientific government advisor on climate change in this country, confirmed that China's efforts are far greater than is commonly expected.
He pointed out that the per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China amounted to six tons per person, while in the United States they were 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to pollution.
