In addition, the steak, the tuna from the can, even the baguette and the chewing gum were peppered with pesticides and other chemical substances.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have brought the presence of nitrates and chloroform to light.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues determined, and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer is "probably undervalued", the study says.
For its part, the Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed "in view of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in diseases of civilisation".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) on the presence of residues identified 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables that are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
